 identify the conditions under which ethnocentrism shapes public opinion. While ethnocentrism is widespread in the United States, the authors demonstrate that its political relevance depends on circumstance. Exploring the implications of these findings for political knowledge, cosmopolitanism, and societies outside the United States, Kinder and Kam add a new dimension to our understanding of how democracy functions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmericansxAttitudes. 0aEthnocentrismxUnited States. 0aEthnocentrismzUnited States. 0aPublic opinionxUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aSocial psychologyxUnited States. 0aSocial psychologyzUnited States. 0aSocial valuesxUnited States. 0aSocial valueszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aethnocentrism, public opinion, assimilation, immigration, history, politics, government, enemy, stereotypes, bias, discrimination, groups, democracy, social programs, reform, marriage, homosexuality, humanitarian assistance, charity, welfare, war on terror, terrorism, violence, power, nonfiction, psychology, values, america first, women, gender, hierarchy, empathy, compassion, emotion, affect.1 aKam, Cindy D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226435725423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226435725/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles